---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
import PipelineStepper from '../../components/interactive/PipelineStepper';
---

<BaseLayout title="One Request, End to End">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L01A" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What does one real inference request look like end to end?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        A single inference step is a pipeline with clear stages. Text goes in. A next-token prediction comes out.
        There is nothing magical about any individual stage — each one is a well-defined transformation.
      </p>
      <p>
        This lesson shows you the whole pipeline at a glance. You do not need to understand each stage deeply yet.
        That is what the rest of the course is for. The point right now is to see the map.
      </p>
      <p>
        We will use this same pipeline as a running example throughout the course.
        Each module will revisit it from a deeper angle.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Interactive — Pipeline Stepper</div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
        Step through each stage of one inference request. Click a stage or use the navigation buttons.
      </p>
      <PipelineStepper client:load />
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Our running example — one step of predicting the next token after "The cat sat":
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-3);">
          <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-3); align-items: flex-start;">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost); min-width: 90px;">Raw text</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-primary);">"The cat sat"</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-3); align-items: flex-start;">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-token); min-width: 90px;">Tokenized</span>
            <span>["The", " cat", " sat"] → [791, 2368, 3290]</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-3); align-items: flex-start;">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-token); min-width: 90px;">Embedded</span>
            <span>3 vectors, each with many numbers (the model's internal width)</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-3); align-items: flex-start;">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-attention); min-width: 90px;">Layers</span>
            <span>N layers transform the hidden states</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-3); align-items: flex-start;">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-logits); min-width: 90px;">Logits</span>
            <span>One score per vocabulary entry for the last token position</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-3); align-items: flex-start;">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-logits); min-width: 90px;">Next token</span>
            <span>" on" (highest-scoring token)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <p>A preview of the shapes you will learn to track through each stage:</p>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px;">
          <div><span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">Token IDs:</span> [3] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">(3 integers)</span></div>
          <div><span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">After embedding:</span> [3, d_model] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">(3 vectors)</span></div>
          <div><span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">After N layers:</span> [3, d_model] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">(same shape, different values)</span></div>
          <div><span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">Logits:</span> [|V|] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">(one score per vocabulary token)</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
          This pipeline is not abstract. Here is where it lives in real code:
        </p>
        <div class="file-path">src/llama-graph.cpp</div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          This file contains the helpers that build each stage of the pipeline:
        </p>
        <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0;"><span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">build_attn()</span> <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">— attention stage</span></li>
          <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0;"><span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">build_ffn()</span> <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">— feed-forward stage</span></li>
          <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0;"><span style="color: var(--sem-router);">build_moe_ffn()</span> <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">— mixture-of-experts stage</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); margin-top: var(--space-3); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
          And here is one complete model that wires them together:
        </p>
        <div class="file-path">src/models/gemma.cpp</div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          You do not need to read these files yet. But they exist, they are real, and by the end of this course you will understand every major section.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          During generation, the model computation (embedding, layers, output projection) runs for every new token. Tokenization happens only once on the input text. The cost of the model stages varies dramatically.
          Understanding where time goes is the goal of the performance modules later in the course.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L01A"
        gateStrength="soft"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L01A-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Place these stages in the correct order: Embedding, Tokenization, Output Logits, Transformer Layers',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Tokenization → Embedding → Transformer Layers → Output Logits', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Embedding → Tokenization → Output Logits → Transformer Layers', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Transformer Layers → Tokenization → Embedding → Output Logits', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'Text is first tokenized into IDs, then embedded into vectors, then transformed through layers, and finally projected to logits.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L01A-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Which stage produces the logits?',
            tag: 'shape',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'The tokenizer', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'The embedding table', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: 'The output head (final projection after the last layer)', isCorrect: true },
            ],
            explanation: 'The output head takes the final hidden state and projects it to a vector of size |V| — one score per vocabulary entry.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
